===Etymology===
{{etyl|ang}} {{term|wif|wīf|lang=ang}} 'woman', from {{proto|Germanic|wīƀam}} (cf. West Frisian {{term|wiif|lang=fy}}, Dutch {{term|wijf}}, Low German {{term|Wief}}, German {{term|Weib}}), from {{proto|Indo-European|gʷíh<sub>2</sub>bʰo-}} (cf. Tocharian B {{term|kwipe|lang=txb}} 'shame; vulva').

===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
{{en-noun|wives}}

# A [[marry|married]] [[woman]], esp. in relation to her spouse.
# The [[female]] of a pair of [[mated]] [[animal]]s.
#: ''A new '''wife''' for the gander is introduced into the pen.''
# {{context|Geordie|dialect}} ([[archaic]]) A [[woman]] ''(compare [[old wife]] and [[aad wife]])''.

====Usage notes====
The singular possessive is ''wife's'', as in "My '''wife's''' mother is my mother-in-law."

